---
import Layout from '~/layouts/PageLayout.astro';
import DocsShell from '~/components/widgets/DocsShell.astro';

const metadata = {
  title: 'Chat mode — Aitroop Docs',
};
---

<Layout metadata={metadata}>
  <DocsShell current="chat">
    <h1>Chat mode</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      Chat is where you figure out what works. It's open-ended, disposable on purpose, and intentionally
      cheaper than building an App. Use it for exploration; save the version that works.
    </p>

    <h2>When to use chat</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>You don't know the right phrasing yet.</strong> The task is clear in your head but you haven't found the prompt that makes the agent produce the output you want.</li>
      <li><strong>One-off work.</strong> You're never going to do this exact task again. Don't bother saving — just chat, get the result, move on.</li>
      <li><strong>Editing an existing Artifact.</strong> An App produced something; you want to make small adjustments without re-running the whole App. Open it in chat, ask for the changes, export.</li>
      <li><strong>Debugging an App.</strong> If a saved App isn't producing what you expect, switch back to chat with the same context and figure out what changed.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>The interface</h2>
    <p>
      A chat has three regions: the conversation thread (left), the Artifact preview pane (right),
      and the toolbar above.
    </p>

    <h3>Conversation thread</h3>
    <p>
      Standard back-and-forth with the agent. Every turn from the agent that produces a deliverable
      shows up as an Artifact attached to that turn — you can keep iterating, and old Artifacts stay
      reachable in the scrollback.
    </p>

    <h3>Artifact preview pane</h3>
    <p>
      The latest Artifact lives here, rendered in full. If it's markdown, you see the rendered document.
      If it's a CSV, you see a table. If it's HTML, you see the page. Click the version drop-down to step
      back through earlier Artifacts in the same conversation.
    </p>

    <h3>Toolbar</h3>
    <p>The actions you'll use most:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Skills</strong> — open the picker to enable or disable Skills for this chat.</li>
      <li><strong>Connects</strong> — see which integrations are authorized and currently in scope.</li>
      <li><strong>Attach</strong> — drop a file directly into the conversation (CSV, PDF, image, code).</li>
      <li><strong>Save as App</strong> — crystallize the current conversation into a reusable App. See <a href="/docs/apps">Apps</a> for the saved-App lifecycle.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Writing good chat messages</h2>
    <p>
      The quality of the agent's first response is heavily shaped by the quality of your first message.
      A useful template covers four parts:
    </p>
    <div class="code-block">
<span style="color:var(--aw-color-text-muted)"># Task</span><br/>
What you want the agent to do, in one or two sentences.<br/>
<br/>
<span style="color:var(--aw-color-text-muted)"># Inputs</span><br/>
The specific data points: dates, names, IDs, file references.<br/>
<br/>
<span style="color:var(--aw-color-text-muted)"># Output</span><br/>
The shape of the answer: markdown / csv / table / etc., and how to structure it.<br/>
<br/>
<span style="color:var(--aw-color-text-muted)"># Constraints</span><br/>
What to include, what to skip, language, length.
    </div>
    <p>
      You don't have to use this template every time. But when something isn't working, adding the
      missing section is usually the fix.
    </p>

    <h2>How the agent uses Skills and Connects</h2>
    <p>
      Skills are tools the agent can call. Connects are accounts the agent can read and write through.
      In Chat, both are always available — the agent decides when to invoke them based on the task.
    </p>
    <p>
      You can see what the agent is doing in real time: tool calls appear inline in the conversation
      with their inputs and results. If the agent tries to use a Connect you haven't authorized, it
      will pause and ask you to authorize first. Authorize once and the Connect is available for every
      future chat and App.
    </p>

    <h2>Attaching files</h2>
    <p>
      Drag a file into the chat (or use the Attach button) and the agent treats it as context.
      Supported types include CSV, PDF, images, code files, and most text formats. The agent can
      parse a CSV row by row, extract text from a PDF, OCR an image, and reason over code.
    </p>
    <p>
      Files attached in chat are available throughout the conversation. If you save the chat as an App,
      the attachment can become a <code>file</code> AppInput so the App expects a fresh upload each run.
    </p>

    <h2>Sandbox and isolation</h2>
    <p>
      Every chat runs in its own isolated sandbox. The agent can execute code, install packages, and
      write to a temp filesystem — none of which touches your machine, your data, or anyone else's chat.
      The sandbox is torn down when the chat ends.
    </p>
    <p>
      If you save the chat as an App, each run of the App also runs in a fresh sandbox. Two people running
      the same App at the same time never see each other's state.
    </p>

    <h2>When to stop chatting and save</h2>
    <p>
      A simple rule: if you've gotten the output you wanted at least once, and you'll need this output
      again with different inputs, save it. Don't keep iterating in chat. Don't re-do the conversation
      next week. Click <strong>Save as App</strong> and parameterize the parts that change.
    </p>
    <p>
      The chat doesn't go away when you save — you can keep iterating after, and re-save the App to
      pick up new changes.
    </p>

    <div class="next-up">
      <span class="label">Next</span>
      <a href="/docs/apps">Apps — the saved-App lifecycle</a>
    </div>
  </DocsShell>
</Layout>
